==Old English==

===Etymology===
Germanic ''*þarf-'', from Indo-European ''*terp-, *trep-''.  Germanic cognates include Old Frisian ''*thurva'', Old Saxon {{Latinx|''thurḅan''}} (Dutch ''[[durven]]''), Old Norse ''[[þurfa]]'' (Swedish ''[[tarva]]''), Old High German ''[[thurfan]]'' (German ''[[dürfen]]''), Gothic *[[𐌸𐌰𐌿𐍂𐌱𐌰]].  The Indo-European root also led to Greek ''[[τερπειν]]'', Old Slavic ''[[trěbě]]'' (Russian ''[[требоватъ]]'').

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/ˈðʊrvɑn/}}

===Verb===
'''þurfan''' (preterite-present: ''3 singular present'' '''[[þearf]]'', ''3 plural present'' '''[[þurfon]]'''; ''3 singular preterite'' '''[[þorfte]]''')

# to [[need]], to be [[obliged]] (to do something)

